'''Jarome Arthur-Leigh Adekunle Tig Junior Elvis Iginla'''<ref name="NYT2002">{{cite news |last=LaPointe |first=Joe |title=Iginla's dream season heads into overtime |work=The New York Times |date=2002-06-18 |url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B00E4DA1F3CF93BA25755C0A9649C8B63 |accessdate=2008-12-14}}</ref><ref name="NHL 406226">{{cite news | url = http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=406226&navid=DL|NHL|home | title = Iginla's name is as big as his game | accessdate = 2009-01-27 | author = Larry Wigge | date = 2009-01-26 |publisher=National Hockey League}}</ref> (born July 1, 1977) is a [[Canada|Canadian]] professional [[ice hockey]] player for the [[Calgary Flames]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). A five-time [[National Hockey League All-Star Game|NHL All-Star]], he is the Flames' all-time leader in goals, points, and games played.  Named the Flames [[Captain (ice hockey)|captain]] at the start of the [[2003<U+2013>04 NHL season|2003<U+2013>04 season]], Iginla has been called the first black captain in NHL history.  He has represented Canada internationally on numerous occasions, helping [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|Team Canada]] to its first Olympic gold medal in 50 years at the [[2002 Winter Olympics]].

As a [[junior ice hockey|junior]], Iginla was a member of two [[Memorial Cup]]-winning teams with the [[Kamloops Blazers]], and was named the [[Western Hockey League]]'s [[Four Broncos Memorial Trophy|Player of the Year]] in [[1995<U+2013>96 WHL season|1996]]. He was selected 11th overall by the [[Dallas Stars]] in the [[1995 NHL Entry Draft]], but was later traded to Calgary and has played his entire professional career with the Flames.  He led the NHL in goals and points in [[2001<U+2013>02 NHL season|2001<U+2013>02]], and won the [[Lester B. Pearson Award]] as its most valuable player as voted by the players.  In [[2003<U+2013>04 NHL season|2003<U+2013>04]], Iginla led the league in goals for the second time and captained the Flames to the [[2004 Stanley Cup Finals|Stanley Cup Finals]], leading the league in playoff scoring.  Iginla [[List of NHL players with 50 goal seasons|scored 50&nbsp;goals]] in a season for a second time in [[2007<U+2013>08 NHL season|2007<U+2013>08]].  Known for his polite and generous nature, Iginla participates in numerous community events, and donates $2,000 to charity for each goal he scores.

==Early life==
Iginla was born in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], July 1, 1977.  His father, a lawyer, was born in [[Nigeria]] and changed his first name from Adekunle to Elvis when he arrived in Canada.<ref name="SI2007">{{cite web |last=Cazeneuve |first=Brian |url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1107127/index.htm |title=Jarome Iginla |work=Sports Illustrated |date=2007-03-05 |accessdate=2008-12-14}}</ref>  His surname means "Big tree" in [[Yoruba language|Yor<U+00F9>b<U+00E1>]], his father's native language.<ref name="Blaze1129">{{cite journal |last=Board |first=Mike |title=Overtime: #12's Top 10 |journal=Blaze Magazine |publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club |year=2008 |date=2008-11-29 |page=pp. 6<U+2013>11}}</ref> Iginla's mother, Susan, is originally from [[Oregon]], and has worked as a massage therapist and music teacher.  Iginla grew up with his mother and grandmother after his parents divorced when he was a year old.<ref name="SI2007" /> While his mother is a [[Buddhism|Buddhist]], he identifies himself as [[Christian]], his father's faith.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.calgarychristian.com/articles/2004/406-jarome_iginla.htm |last=Gulbranson |first=Davin | title=Jarome Iginla<U+2014>The Smile Says It All |work=City Light News |accessdate=2009-02-27}}</ref>

In addition to hockey, Iginla played [[baseball]] as a young man and was the [[catcher]] on the Canadian National Junior team.<ref name="Blaze1129" />  He grew up admiring other black hockey players, including [[Edmonton Oilers]] [[goaltender]] [[Grant Fuhr]].  Emulating Fuhr, Iginla played goaltender in his first two years of organized hockey before switching to the [[Winger (hockey)|right wing]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Amber |first=David |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/columns/story?id=2205382 |title=Facing Off: Q&A with Jarome Iginla |publisher=ESPN |date=2005-10-28 |accessdate=2009-01-04}}</ref>  He played his entire minor hockey career in St. Albert, leading the [[Alberta Midget Hockey League]] in scoring as a 15-year-old with 87&nbsp;points for the St. Albert Midget Raiders in 1992<U+2013>93.<ref name="Blaze1129" />

==Junior career==
Iginla played three years with the [[Kamloops Blazers]] of the [[Western Hockey League]] (WHL).  As a 16-year-old in [[1993<U+2013>94 WHL season|1993<U+2013>94]], he recorded six goals and 29&nbsp;points in 48 regular season games before playing an additional 19 in the playoffs.<ref name="LOH">{{cite web |url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net:8080/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=10613 |title=Player Profile<U+2014>Jarome Iginla |publisher=Hockey Hall of Fame |accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>  The Blazers captured both the [[Ed Chynoweth Cup|league title]] and the [[1994 Memorial Cup|1994]] [[Memorial Cup]], Canada's national junior championship.<ref>{{Cite book|editor=Flett, Cory and Watts, Jessie|title=2008<U+2013>09 WHL Guide|publisher=Western Hockey League|page=206}}</ref>  In reference to the Blazers' dominance of the league at the time (they had won their third WHL title in five seasons), Iginla described the expectations of success as being similar to those placed the [[Montreal Canadiens]], the NHL's most successful franchise: "When you put on a Blazers jersey, it's like putting on the Canadiens'.  You've got to perform."<ref>{{cite book |last=Lapp |first=Richard |last2=Macaulay |first2=Alec |title=The Memorial Cup: Canada's National Junior Hockey Championship |publisher=Harbour Publishing |year=1997 |isbn=1-55015-170-4 |page=260}}</ref>

Iginla scored 33&nbsp;goals and 71&nbsp;points in [[1994<U+2013>95 WHL season|1994<U+2013>95]], his first full WHL season.<ref name="LOH" /> The Blazers repeated as league champions, earning a trip to the [[1995 Memorial Cup]].  Iginla scored five goals in the tournament to lead the Blazers to a second consecutive national championship.  He received the [[George Parsons Trophy]] as the most sportsmanlike player of the tournament.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lapp |first=Richard |last2=Macaulay |first2=Alec |title=The Memorial Cup: Canada's National Junior Hockey Championship |publisher=Harbour Publishing |year=1997 |isbn=1-55015-170-4 |page=267}}</ref>

The [[Dallas Stars]] selected Iginla with their first round selection, 11th overall, in the [[1995 NHL Entry Draft]]; however, on December 20, 1995, they traded him to the [[Calgary Flames]], along with [[Corey Millen]], for forward [[Joe Nieuwendyk]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Duhatschek |first=Eric |title=Flames bank on future |work=Calgary Herald |date=1995-12-21 |page=C1}}</ref>

In his final season in Kamloops in [[1995<U+2013>96 WHL season|1995<U+2013>96]], Iginla finished fourth in league scoring with 136&nbsp;points, including 63&nbsp;goals in 63&nbsp;games played, and was awarded the [[Four Broncos Memorial Trophy]] as the league's most outstanding player.<ref>{{Cite book|editor=Flett, Cory and Watts, Jessie|title=2008<U+2013>09 WHL Guide|publisher=Western Hockey League|page=199}}</ref> The Blazers were upset in the Western Conference final by the [[Spokane Chiefs]], but Iginla still finished fourth in playoff scoring, recording 29 points in 16 games.<ref>{{Cite book|editor=Flett, Cory and Watts, Jessie|title=2008<U+2013>09 WHL Guide|publisher=Western Hockey League|page=165}}</ref>  His performance during the season earned him an invitation to play for [[Canada men's national junior ice hockey team|Team Canada]] at the [[1996 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]] in [[Boston]], where he helped Canada to its fourth consecutive gold medal.<ref name="TSN-WJHC">{{cite web |url=http://www.tsn.ca/World_jrs/feature/?fid=1047&hubname= |title=1996 - Boston, United States |publisher=The Sports Network |accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref>

==NHL career==
[[Image:Iginla warming up.jpg|thumb|right|170px|Iginla warming up before a game in March 2006.]]
Iginla made his NHL debut in the [[1996 Stanley Cup Playoffs]], as he was signed to a contract and flown to Calgary immediately after his junior season ended in Kamloops.  He appeared in two games for the Flames in their series against the [[Chicago Blackhawks]].  In doing so, he became the first 18-year-old to play for the Flames since [[Dan Quinn]] in 1983.<ref>{{cite news |title='Iguana' enjoys heat |last=Board |first=Mike |work=Calgary Herald |date=1996-04-22 |page=D3}}</ref>  In his first NHL game, Iginla assisted on a [[Theoren Fleury]] goal to record his first point;<ref>{{cite news |last=Duhatschek |first=Eric |title=A quick learner |work=Calgary Herald |date=1996-04-23 |page=D1}}</ref> he scored his first goal in his second game.<ref>{{cite news |last=Duhatschek |first=Eric |title=Heartbreak |work=Calgary Herald |date=1996-04-24 |page=C1}}</ref>  He remained with the Flames, and played his first NHL season in [[1996<U+2013>97 NHL season|1996<U+2013>97]].  He earned a spot on that year's [[NHL All-Rookie Team]] and finished as the runner-up to [[Bryan Berard]] in voting for the [[Calder Memorial Trophy]] as rookie of the year after leading all first-year players in scoring with 50&nbsp;points.<ref name="0809MediaGuide">{{cite book |title=2008<U+2013>09 Calgary Flames Media Guide |publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club |editor=Hanlon, Peter and Kelso, Sean |pages=59<U+2013>61 |url=http://downloads.flames.nhl.com/other/2008CalgaryFlamesMediaGuide_web.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref>

By his third season, [[1998<U+2013>99 NHL season|1998<U+2013>99]], Iginla led the Flames in goals with 28.<ref name="0809MediaGuide" />  His success complicated negotiations for a new contract, as he and the Flames struggled to agree on a new deal following the season.  Hoping to help resolve the contract impasse, he agreed to attend training camp without a contract, and purchased his own insurance as the team would not have been responsible financially if he suffered an injury.  He remained without a contract at the start of the [[1999<U+2013>2000 NHL season|1999<U+2013>00 season]] and missed the first three games as a holdout before signing a deal worth [[United States dollar|US$]]4.9 million, plus bonuses.<ref name="0809MediaGuide" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Board |first=Mike |title=Iginla signs 3-year deal |work=Calgary Herald |date=1999-10-09 |page=E1}}</ref>  He finished the year with career highs in goals (29) and points (63). He then topped both marks in [[2000<U+2013>01 NHL season|2000<U+2013>01]] by recording 31&nbsp;goals and 71&nbsp;points.<ref name="0809MediaGuide" />

After participating in Canada's Olympic summer camp before the season, Iginla again set new personal highs in [[2001<U+2013>02 NHL season|2001<U+2013>02]] when he registered 52&nbsp;goals and 96&nbsp;points. This season elevated Iginla to superstar status.<ref>{{cite web |last=Allen |first=Kevin |url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/columns/allen/2002-03-05-allen.htm |title=Iginla ready to break the bank |work=USA Today |date=2002-03-05 |accessdate=2008-12-15}}</ref>  He earned the [[Art Ross Trophy|Art Ross]] and [[Maurice "Rocket" Richard Trophy|Maurice Richard]] trophies as the NHL's leading point and goal scorer, respectively.<ref name="0809MediaGuide" />  He was also awarded the [[Lester B. Pearson Award]] as the league's most valuable player as voted by his peers, and was a nominee for both the [[Hart Memorial Trophy]] and the [[King Clancy Memorial Trophy]].  The Hart Trophy voting proved to be controversial: Iginla tied Canadiens goaltender [[Jos<U+00E9> Th<U+00E9>odore]] in voting points, but received fewer first place votes than Th<U+00E9>odore.<ref>{{cite book |last=Harris |first=Cecil |title=Breaking the Ice: The Black Experience in Professional Hockey |publisher=Insomniac Press |year=2003 |ISBN=1-894663-58-6 |page=20}}</ref> However, one voter, rumoured to be from [[Quebec]]<U+2014>Th<U+00E9>odore and the Canadiens' home province<U+2014>inexplicably left Iginla off his ballot.  As a result of the controversy that followed, the Professional Hockey Writers Association changed the rules on how its members voted for the award to prevent a reoccurrence.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dowbiggin |first=Bruce |url=http://www2.canada.com/calgaryherald/news/story.html?id=5550ffa5-080c-439f-8a58-c4ea3ea66b70 |title=Hart irony may burn Iginla |work=Calgary Herald |date=2008-03-07 |accessdate=2009-05-20}}</ref> Iginla was a member of [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|Team Canada]]'s [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] [[gold medal]]-winning hockey team in 2002. 

There were fears Iginla would again hold out after his contract expired following the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2002/08/20/iginla020820.html |title=Jarome Iginla may hold out: report |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=2002-08-21 |accessdate=2008-12-15}}</ref> These fears were unfounded, however, as he signed a two-year, $13 million deal before the season and was looked on to again lead the Flames offensively.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dolezar |first=John A. |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/hockey/news/2002/09/16/2002_flamespreview/ |title=2002<U+2013>03 season preview <U+2013> Calgary Flames |publisher=CNN Sports Illustrated |date=2002-09-16 |accessdate=2008-12-15}}</ref>  Iginla fell back to 67&nbsp;points in [[2002<U+2013>03 NHL season|2002<U+2013>03]] as injuries, including a lingering finger dislocation following a fight, diminished his play.<ref>{{cite web |last=Canella |first=Stephen |url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1031196/index.htm |title=Catching Fire |work=Sports Illustrated |date=2004-02-16 |accessdate=2009-01-04}}</ref> His 35 goals were still enough to lead the Flames for the fourth time in five seasons.<ref name="0809MediaGuide" />  Despite his offensive contributions, the Flames missed the playoffs for the seventh consecutive season.<ref>{{cite book |title=2008<U+2013>09 Calgary Flames Media Guide |publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club |editor=Hanlon, Peter and Kelso, Sean |page=133 |url=http://downloads.flames.nhl.com/other/2008CalgaryFlamesMediaGuide_web.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref>

===Captaincy===
At the start of the [[2003<U+2013>04 NHL season|2003<U+2013>04 season]], Iginla was named the 18th captain in Flames franchise history, and 14th since the team moved to Calgary from [[Atlanta]] in 1980.<ref>{{cite book |title=2008<U+2013>09 Calgary Flames Media Guide |publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club |editor=Hanlon, Peter and Kelso, Sean |page=131 |url=http://downloads.flames.nhl.com/other/2008CalgaryFlamesMediaGuide_web.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref>  His predecessor as captain, [[Craig Conroy]], cited Iginla's experience and leadership for his decision to relinquish the captaincy to Iginla. "He was a leader on that team and old enough to where he'd been there a long time. It was time for him. He took us to the Stanley Cup Final that year so it worked out pretty well."<ref name="Captain">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=396926 |title=Iginla honored to be captain of Flames |publisher=National Hockey League |last=Rosen |first=Dan |date=2008-12-09 |accessdate=2008-12-10}}</ref> Iginla was reported to be the first black captain in NHL history,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?id=1633595 |title=Iginla becomes first black captain in NHL history |accessdate=2008-04-17 |date=2003-10-08 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> though former Blackhawks captain [[Dirk Graham]], who is of African descent, has also been said to hold that honour.<ref>{{cite web |last=McKeon |first=Ross |url=http://ca.sports.yahoo.com/nhl/news?slug=rm-oree011708&prov=yhoo&type=lgns |title=O'Ree had vision as NHL pioneer |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |date=2008-01-16 |accessdate=2009-05-20}}</ref>

[[File:Jarome Iginla silver stick.JPG|thumb|left|[[Darryl Sutter]] presents Iginla with a silver stick in honour of his becoming the Flames all-time scoring leader.]]
Iginla responded to being named captain by capturing his second [[Maurice "Rocket" Richard Trophy|Rocket Richard Trophy]], sharing the goal-scoring title with [[Ilya Kovalchuk]] and [[Rick Nash]] with 41&nbsp;goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2004/04/04/richard_trophy040404.html |title=St. Louis wins Art Ross; Iginla shares Richard Trophy |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=2004-04-05 |accessdate=2008-12-15}}</ref>  The Flames qualified for the [[2004 Stanley Cup Playoffs]] as the sixth seed, the team's first playoff appearance in eight years.<ref>{{cite web |last=Johnson |first=George |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/playoffs2004/columns/story?columnist=johnson_george&id=1807558 |title=Sutter attitude goes a long way |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-05-23 |accessdate=2008-12-15}}</ref>  Iginla led all playoff scorers with 13&nbsp;goals as he captained the Flames to their first [[2004 Stanley Cup Finals|Stanley Cup finals]] appearance in 15&nbsp;years.  The Flames were unable to defeat the [[Tampa Bay Lightning]], however, falling to the [[Eastern Conference (NHL)|Eastern Conference]] champions in seven games.  A dejected Iginla sat in the Flames locker room after the final game and was met by his father, who told his son that "I'm proud of you.  All of Canada is proud of you."<ref>{{cite web |last=Adelson |first=Eric |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/playoffs2004/columns/story?id=1817708 |title=Iginla gives Flames hope, even in defeat |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-06-14 |accessdate=2008-12-15}}</ref>  

While he was hailed as the best player in the world following his performance in the playoffs,<ref>{{cite news |last=Heika |first=Mike |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-7592663_ITM |title=Iginla shining bright for Flames, NHL |work=Dallas Morning News |date=2004-05-28 |accessdate=2008-12-18}}</ref><ref name="Impact">{{cite web |last=Coffey |first=Phil |url=http://www.nhl.com/intheslot/read/impact/2003_04/cup/iginla.html |title=The sky's the limit for Iginla |publisher=National Hockey League |date=2004-06 |accessdate=2009-01-04}}</ref> Iginla spent the [[2004<U+2013>05 NHL lockout]] focused on improving his game further.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lawrence |first=Andrew |url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1113192/index.htm |title=Power Train |work=Sports Illustrated |date=2005-10-10 |accessdate=2008-12-18}}</ref>  Following the lockout, he was named as one of six player representatives on the newly created NHL competition committee, with a mandate to suggest recommendations for ways to improve the game.  He held this position until early 2008.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.com/Sports/article/417009 |title=NHL competition committee gets a facelift |work=Toronto Star |date=2008-04-22 |accessdate=2008-12-18}}</ref>

On December 7, 2006, Iginla reached a career milestone when he scored his 300th career goal and 600th career point against the [[Minnesota Wild]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2006/12/09/canucks-flames.html |title=Flames, Canucks clash in Calgary |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=2006-12-09 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref> He was expected to play in the [[55th National Hockey League All-Star Game|2007 NHL All-Star Game]] in Dallas; however he missed the game with a knee injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/allstar2007/news/story?id=2731958 |title=Brodeur, Selanne, 28 others join list of NHL All-Stars |publisher=ESPN |date=2007-01-18 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>  The injury kept him out of 12 games in [[2006<U+2013>07 NHL season|2006<U+2013>07]].  He nevertheless scored 94&nbsp;points, including a career-high 55&nbsp;assists.<ref name="0809MediaGuide" /> 

{{Quote box| quote  ="I think it was a very classy thing to do. I think Jarome is one of the most classy players in the league, not only that, he<U+2019>s probably the best player in the league. When you have a captain like that, it was certainly a very classy move on their part, no doubt."|align=right |width=30%|source=[[Trevor Linden]], after Iginla led a procession of Flames players in shaking Linden's hand following his final NHL game, April 5, 2008<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/team/app?articleid=359382&page=NewsPage&service=page|title=End of An Era?|accessdate=2009-01-02|publisher=Vancouver Canucks Hockey Club|year=2008 |author=Dhillon, Sunny}}</ref>}}

The [[2007<U+2013>08 NHL season|2007<U+2013>08]] season saw Iginla post his second career 50&nbsp;goal season, adding 48&nbsp;assists for a career high 98&nbsp;points,<ref name="0809MediaGuide" /> good for third overall in the league.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/statistics?season=2008&stat=nhlscoring |title=2007<U+2013>08 NHL scoring <U+2013> points |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref> He was voted to the starting line-up of the [[56th National Hockey League All-Star Game|2008 NHL All-Star Game]] along with teammate [[Dion Phaneuf]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Podell |first=Ira |url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/nhl/2008-01-08-all-star-starters_N.htm |title=Red Wings, Penguins' Crosby top NHL All-Star voting |work=USA Today |date=2008-01-08 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref> and was named captain of the Western All-Star Team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tsn.ca/story/?id=228282&hubname=nhl |title=Iginla, Lecavalier to handle captain duties |publisher=The Sports Network |date=2008-01-26 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>   He broke the Flames' franchise record for games played when he played his 804th career game on November 29, 2007, against the [[Anaheim Ducks]].  He also broke [[Theoren Fleury]]'s franchise record for goals when he scored his 365th on March 10, 2008, against the [[St. Louis Blues (hockey)|St. Louis Blues]].<ref name="0809MediaGuide" />  Iginla was nominated as a Hart Trophy finalist for league most valuable player for the third time, though he again did not win the award.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iginla named Hart Trophy finalist |publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club |date=2008-04-29 |url=http://flames.nhl.com/team/app?articleid=361996&page=NewsPage&service=page |accessdate=2009-05-20}}</ref>  During the season, he signed a five-year contract extension with the Flames at $7 million per season.<ref>{{cite web |last=Duhatschek |first=Eric |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20080304.wsptduha4/BNStory/Sports/columnists |title=Iginla enjoying the ride |work=The Globe and Mail |date=2008-03-04 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>

Iginla continued his pursuit of Fleury's franchise record of 830&nbsp;points in [[2008<U+2013>09 NHL season|2008<U+2013>09]].  He recorded his 800th point with a first period assist against the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] on December 19, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |last=Board |first=Mike |url=http://flames.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=399212 |title=Iginla notches 800th point |publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club |date=2008-12-19 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>  He ended 2008 with a career high five points in a New Year's Eve game against the [[Edmonton Oilers]].  He had 14 previous four point games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehockeynews.com/articles/21862-Iginla-Cammalleri-both-tally-five-points-each-as-the-Flames-beat-Oilers-64.html |title=Iginla, Cammalleri both tally five points each as the Flames beat Oilers 6-4 |work=The Hockey News |date=2009-01-01 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>  In January, he was named to the [[2009 NHL All-Star Game]] in [[Montreal]], his fifth such selection.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Holland |first=Brad |url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=402614&navid=DL|NHL|home |title=Defense sets the table for Western All-Stars |publisher=National Hockey League |date=2009-01-07 |accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>  Representing the [[Western Conference (NHL)|Western Conference]], Iginla scored his first career NHL All-Star Game goal in a 12<U+2013>11 shootout loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=264648&lid=headline&lpos=topStory_main |title=Kovalev scores shootout winner as East beats West |publisher=The Sports Network |date=2009-01-26 |accessdate=2009-03-01}}</ref> He passed Fleury as the Flames' all-time scoring leader on March 1, 2009, scoring five points, including his 400th career goal, in an 8<U+2013>6 loss to the Lightning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=269423&lid=sublink02&lpos=headlines_main |title=Lightning rain on Iginla's record-setting night |publisher=The Sports Network |date=2009-03-01 |accessdate=2009-03-02}}</ref>  He finished the season with 35&nbsp;goals and 89&nbsp;points, but a disappointing playoff performance led to questions of whether he had been playing with an injury.  Iginla quickly denied the rumour, admitted that he had not played with the level of consistency he expected and stated that he would spend the summer focused on improving his play in [[2009<U+2013>10 NHL season|2009<U+2013>10]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Hall |first=Vicki |url=http://www.calgaryherald.com/business/Iginla+nixes+injury+rumour/1549050/story.html |title=Iginla nixes injury rumour |work=Calgary Herald |date=2009-04-30 |accessdate=2009-05-20}}</ref>

