Iginla first represented Canada at the 1994 [[Ivan Hlinka Memorial Tournament|Nations Cup]], an unsanctioned tournament for players under the age of 18.  He led Canada in scoring with five goals and nine points as it won the gold medal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hockeycanada.ca/4/2/2/0/index1.shtml |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20060514092829/http://www.hockeycanada.ca/4/2/2/0/index1.shtml |title=La Copa Mexico 1994 |publisher=Hockey Canada |archivedate=2006-05-14 |accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>  Two years later, he joined the [[Canada men's national junior ice hockey team|national junior team]] at the [[1996 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]].  He led the tournament in scoring with five goals and 12&nbsp;points as Canada won its fourth consecutive gold medal.  He was named an all-star and the tournament's top forward.<ref name="TSN-WJHC" /><ref name="Blaze1129" />  One year later, Iginla played in his first tournament with the [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|senior team]], competing at the [[1997 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|1997 World Championships]] as a 19-year-old, the youngest player on the team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hockeycanada.ca/index.php/ci_id/4722/la_id/1.htm |title=1997 IIHF World Championship |publisher=Hockey Canada |accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>  He recorded two goals and three assists in 11&nbsp;games as Canada won the gold medal.<ref name="LOH" />

An invitation to join Team Canada at the [[Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics|2002 Winter Olympics]] helped Iginla emerge as a star player.  He scored two goals in the gold medal game, a 5<U+2013>2 victory over the [[United States men's national ice hockey team|United States]], as Canada won its first Olympic gold medal in 50&nbsp;years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/olympics/2002/ice_hockey/news/2002/02/24/usa_canada_ap/ |title=Stand on guard for thee |publisher=CNN Sports Illustrated |date=2002-02-24 |accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> He also represented Canada at the [[2004 World Cup of Hockey]], playing on a line with [[Joe Sakic]] and [[Mario Lemieux]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=1877692 |title=Brodeur nabs first shutout of World Cup |publisher=ESPN |date=2008-09-08 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref> where Canada again won the gold medal.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lapointe |first=Joe |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2004/09/15/sports/hockey/15hockey.html?pagewanted=print&position= |title=Canada's Cup Victory May End Up Half Empty |work=The New York Times |date=2004-09-15 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>  

Iginla participated in his second Olympics at the [[2006 Winter Olympics|2006 Turin]] games, recording three points in six games.<ref name="LOH" />  The Canadians were unable to defend their 2002 gold medal, losing to the Russians in the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/winter06/hockey/news/story?id=2341523 |title=Gretzky questions future role with Hockey Canada |publisher=ESPN |date=2006-02-23 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>  He is expected to be a top player for Canada at the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] in Vancouver,<ref>{{cite web |last=Barnes |first=Dan |url=http://www.nationalpost.com/sports/story.html?id=1073887 |title=Team Canada's Olympic dream team takes shape |work=National Post |date=2008-12-14 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref> and is a candidate to serve as the team's captain.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wyman |first=Ted |url=http://lfpress.ca/newsstand/Sports/Hockey/2008/12/21/7818186-sun.html |title=Cream of the crop |work=London Free Press |date=2008-12-21 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>

==Playing style==
[[File:Iginla v Lecavalier.JPG|thumb|left|Iginla faces off against [[Vincent Lecavalier]].]]
Iginla is considered to be one of the NHL's pre-eminent [[Power forward (ice hockey)|power forwards]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Nichols |first=Chris |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/2008/09/18/nichols_power_forwards/ |title=NHL Power Brokers |publisher=Rogers Sportsnet |date=2008-09-18 |accessdate=2009-01-04}}</ref>  Upon entering the league, he tried to emulate players like [[Brendan Shanahan]] and [[Keith Tkachuk]], hoping to match their combination of finesse and physicality.<ref name="Impact" />  He is one of the most consistent scorers in the league; between 1998 and 2008, only [[Jarom<U+00ED>r J<U+00E1>gr]] scored more NHL goals than Iginla.<ref name="Consistency">{{cite web |last=Cruikshank |first=Scott |url=http://www2.canada.com/saskatoonstarphoenix/news/sports/story.html?id=7f057796-13e3-4995-b54c-5a5028b0d108 |title=Iginla's scoring consistency amazes most |work=Saskatoon Star-Phoenix |date=2008-01-04 |accessdate=2009-05-28}}</ref> Even so, scouting reports have argued that Iginla's lack of speed makes it easier for opponents to isolate him and restrict his ability to move if his teammates rely on him too much to lead the offence.<ref name="TSN2004Bio">{{cite news |last=Yorio |first=Kara |title=Scouting Report: Jarome Iginla, RW, Calgary Flames |work=The Sporting News |date=2004-03-15 |volume=228 |issue=11 |page=61}}</ref>

The abuse he faced at the hands of opponents early in his NHL career prompted Iginla's coaches to work at developing his physical play.  While he was not enthusiastic about fighting, Iginla accepted then head coach [[Brian Sutter]]'s arguments that he needed to adopt a more aggressive style to improve as a player.  Iginla is most effective when he has room to manoeuvre, and to create that space, he had to intimidate his opponents.<ref>{{cite news |last=Maki |first=Allan |title=Sutter tries to light flame under Iginla |work=Globe and Mail |date=1998-10-16 |page=S5}}</ref>  The lessons Iginla learned have carried throughout his career.   "You've got a power forward who does it all," said [[Craig Conroy]]. "I mean, he'll fight, and hit, and score goals.  Maybe it's not the end-to-end rushes, but he does all those little things that win games and get things done."<ref name="Avery">{{cite web |last=Hall |first=Vicki |url=http://www.canada.com/calgaryherald/news/sports/story.html?id=717c5c54-855e-42cd-9d43-d02fba8080bc |title=Avery takes jab at Iginla |work=Calgary Herald |date=2008-10-09 |accessdate=2009-01-04}}</ref> His opponents also respect his play.  [[Rob Blake]] said that while Iginla is not known for fancy play, "he'll run you over. Or he'll fight somebody. And then he'll score a goal. He does pretty much everything you'd want a guy to do."<ref name="Consistency" />

Iginla has recorded several [[Gordie Howe hat trick]]s.<ref name="0809MediaGuide" /> His fights, including on with Tampa Bay star [[Vincent Lecavalier]] in the [[2004 Stanley Cup Finals]], have had a motivating effect on his play and that of his teammates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/playoffs2004/news/story?id=1812373 |title=Calgary wins with intensity, goaltending |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-05-30 |accessdate=2009-05-28}}</ref>  Iginla has suffered injuries as a result of his fighting, including a broken hand from a 2003 fight with [[Bill Guerin]] of the [[Dallas Stars]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Maki |first=Allan |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/article734282.ece |title=Iginla says fight not to blame for injured knee |work=Globe and Mail |accessdate=2009-05-28}}</ref>  His physical style of play also leads to a greater risk of persistent injuries and [[Penalty (ice hockey)|penalties]].<ref name="TSN2004Bio" />

He commands the respect of his peers, and has been known to stand up to the coaching staff to defend a fellow player.  Former teammate [[Andrew Ference]] once described following Iginla as like "following a friend".<ref name="Consistency" /> Preferring to lead by example, Iginla is not regarded as a vocal captain.  He likes to speak with players individually, and tries to ensure that all of his teammates are comfortable.<ref name="Captain" />  He was named a finalist for the [[Mark Messier Leadership Award]] in 2009, along with [[Sidney Crosby]] and [[Zdeno Ch<U+00E1>ra]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalpost.com/sports/story.html?id=1654916 |title=Iginla, Chara, Crosby up for leadership award |work=National Post |date=2009-06-03 |accessdate=2009-06-03}}</ref>

== Off the ice ==
Iginla married his high school sweetheart, Kara, and the couple has three children: Jade, Tij and Joe.  They had been dating since they were in the eighth grade.<ref name="Blaze1129" />  He has two brothers, Jason and Stephen, and two sisters, Theresa and Elizabeth.<ref>{{cite book |last=Elicksen |first=Debbie |url=http://books.google.ca/books?id=xiekI_Yuph8C&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=Jarome+Iginla+NHL+diversity&source=bl&ots=clt-QxOlW8&sig=Eti3ubLyIf3VKZrZUQbVFSeaBBg&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=4&ct=result#PPA6,M1 |title=Positive Sports |publisher=Freelance Communications |date=2003 |page=90 |ISBN=0973023732}}</ref>  He is an avid golfer and a regular participant in the Calgary Flames Celebrity Charity Golf Classic.<ref name="Blaze1129" />

He is well known for his kind-hearted nature.  Former Flames general manager [[Craig Button]] described Iginla as being grounded: "he doesn't carry himself with any attitude or arrogance. He's confident in his abilities. He's self-assured. He's genuine. He's a better person than he is a player, and we all know what kind of player he is."<ref>{{cite web |last=Ross |first=Sherry |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/sports/2002/10/06/2002-10-06_fanning_the_flames__jarome_i.html |title=Jarome Iginla becoming hottest ticket in Canada |work=New York Daily News |date=2002-10-06 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>  In 2002, while in [[Salt Lake City]] for the [[2002 Winter Olympic Games|Winter Olympic Games]], Iginla struck up a conversation with four Calgarians sitting next to his table, and found out they were sleeping in their car outside of the hotel. He excused himself from the conversation, and booked them accommodations at his own expense at the hotel his family was staying in.<ref>{{cite web |last=Francis |first=Eric |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Columnists/Francis/2007/11/30/4697730-sun.html |title=Iggy's Salt of the Earth |work=Calgary Sun |date=2007-11-03 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>

Since 2002,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canoe.ca/WHLNews0102/0726.html |title=Willie O'Ree to appear at Jarome Iginla Hockey School |publisher=Canoe.ca |date=2002-07-26 |accessdate=2008-12-16}}</ref> he has operated the Jarome Iginla Hockey School in Calgary as a non-profit organization, donating proceeds to the Diabetes Research Association.<ref name="Blaze1129" /> In 2004, he was awarded the [[NHL Foundation Player Award]] for his community service and the [[King Clancy Memorial Trophy]] in recognition of his humanitarian contributions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net:8080/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SilverwareTrophyWinner.jsp?tro=KCT&year=2003-04 |title=2003<U+2013>04 King Clancy Memorial Trophy winner <U+2013> Jarome Iginla |publisher=Hockey Hall of Fame |accessdate=2008-12-16}}</ref>  Iginla supports many charities. In 2000, he began donating $1,000 per goal he scored to [[KidSport]], a figure he doubled to $2,000 in 2005.  From 2000 through to the end of the 2008 season he donated $430,000 from this initiative.<ref name="Blaze1129" /> 

Iginla is a part owner of the [[Kamloops Blazers]] of the [[Western Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blazerhockey.com/content/team/owners.php |title=Meet the Kamloops Blazers owners |publisher=Kamloops Blazers Hockey Club |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>  He purchased a minority share in the franchise, along with fellow NHL players [[Shane Doan]], [[Mark Recchi]] and [[Darryl Sydor]], in October 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whl.ca/whl-board-of-governors-approve-sale-of-the-kamloops-blazers-p125665 |title=WHL Board of Governors Approve Sale of the Kamloops Blazers |publisher=Western Hockey League |date=2007-10-10 |accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref>  He is also an ambassador with the [[NHL Diversity]] program, which supports youth hockey organizations that offer economically disadvantaged kids the opportunity to play.<ref>{{cite book |last=Elicksen |first=Debbie |url=http://books.google.ca/books?id=xiekI_Yuph8C&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=Jarome+Iginla+NHL+diversity&source=bl&ots=clt-QxOlW8&sig=Eti3ubLyIf3VKZrZUQbVFSeaBBg&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=4&ct=result#PPA6,M1 |title=Positive Sports |publisher=Freelance Communications |date=2003 |page=49 |ISBN=0973023732}}</ref>  Since 2008, he has been a hockey spokesperson for [[Scotiabank]], appearing in commercials and at events supporting its grassroots hockey programs,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnw.ca/fr/releases/archive/October2008/02/c2694.html |title=Calgary Flames Captain Jarome Iginla Laces Up to Join Scotiabank's 2008-2009 NHL Lineup as Special Advisor on Hockey |publisher=Bank of Nova Scotia |date=2008-10-02 |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> as well as for [[Samsung Group|Samsung Canada]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Dickie |first=Mary |url=http://www.strategymag.com/articles/magazine/20090101/biz.html |title=Samsung's human touch |work=Strategy Magazine |date=2009-01 |publisher=Brunico Communications |page=p. 10}}</ref>

